<body>
<p>There comes a time in the life of all health educators when you have a proposal you want others to buy into, a concept that you want to actualize, or an idea whose time has come. When that time does come, you’ll need to identify who the decision makers are and be able to make a compelling case for those ideas, articulate your ideas so convincingly, present those cases so effectively, communicate your commitment to the concept in language so forceful, state the merits of putting the idea into action so persuasively, and state the value of the investment in spite of potential challenges, risks or pitfalls involved in such a gripping manner that you become an irresistible force. In other words, to reduce the likelihood that your request will be denied, you’ll need to build and present a compelling business case.</p>
<p>A business case is a tool for anticipating the financial and business consequences of an organizational initiative. Not having or not using such a tool will result in organizations missing valuable opportunities and making less-than-best decisions due to poorly constructed and communicated proposals.</p>
<p>The purpose of this tool is to help you construct a clear and compelling business case that enables your organization and your (potential) funders to make better decisions. As fund-raisers, advocates, membership recruiters, program directors, and administrators, health educators should know how to develop and present a powerful business case to decision makers. It will give you a major advantage over your competitors!</p>
<p>Information and ideas for this tool were drawn from a variety of Internet sources and our own experiences working with organizations developing business cases for fund-raising purposes.</p>
<sec id="section1-1524839912456534">
<title>Definitions</title>
<sec id="section2-1524839912456534">
<title>Business Case (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>; <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1524839912456534">Mykrantz, 2007</xref>)</title>
<list id="list1-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Concise verbal or written proposal</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Prerequisite for initiating new idea/project</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Attention grabbing/air-tight</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>“. . . dollars and cents justification for taking some action or making some investment in the business” (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1524839912456534">Mykrantz, 2007</xref>, p. 1)</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States problem</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Describes proposed solution</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Explains what planned, why good idea, expected outcomes, value to organization</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States cost of implementing recommended solution</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Outlines return on investment (ROI)/costs avoided if proposed solution implemented</p></list-item>
</list>
</sec>
<sec id="section3-1524839912456534">
<title>Return on Investment (ROI) Source (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list2-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Revenue anticipated to be generated directly from expenditures</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Measured in time, money</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Described in ROI statement</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States when money spent recovered</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States income to be generated</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Includes range of “return” sources
<list id="list3-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Existing revenue sources</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>New revenue sources</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>May include nonmonetary “returns” like “good will”</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section4-1524839912456534">
<title>Cost Avoidance (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list4-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Action taken to decrease current costs/prevent future costs</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>“Return” = money saved, not revenue generated</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section5-1524839912456534">
<title>Direct Costs (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list5-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Variable costs/cost of goods sold</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Specifically associated with particular product/activity</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Expenses of manufacturing product, producing service</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Examples:
<list id="list6-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Speakers’ honoraria</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Training materials</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Room rental</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Salaries/fringe benefits</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Travel</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Equipment</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Supplies</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Professional development</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Consulting services</p></list-item></list></p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section6-1524839912456534">
<title>Indirect Costs (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list7-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Fixed or variable costs: overhead, general/administrative</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Not tied to any one particular project
<list id="list8-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Heat</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Lighting</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Air conditioning</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Accounting services</p></list-item></list></p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section7-1524839912456534">
<title>Profit Center (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list9-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Part of organization/program making more money than spending</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Example:
<list id="list10-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Prevention program operation costs: $4 million annually</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Saves $1 billion in health care costs annually</p></list-item></list></p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section8-1524839912456534">
<title>Cost Center (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list11-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Part of organization/program making less money than operation costs</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Example:
<list id="list12-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Popular risk reduction operation costs: $50,000 annually</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Brings in token client payments: $15,000 annually</p></list-item></list></p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section9-1524839912456534">
<title>SWOT (Strengths, Weaknesses, Opportunities, Threats) Analysis</title>
<list id="list13-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Strategic planning process conducted of organization’s/proposed plan (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
</sec>
<sec id="section10-1524839912456534">
<title>Business Case Development/Delivery Process</title>
<list id="list14-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Have idea</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Think through idea</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Play devil’s advocate with self</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Invite others to critique idea</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Set aside time for research</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Recruit assistants/collaborators</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Identify decision makers</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Analyze decision makers</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Learn how organization works:
<list id="list15-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Where/why makes/loses money</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Critical success measures</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Factors affecting profitability</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Actions that build competitive advantage</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Draft business case</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Test for relevance to decision maker</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Practice presentation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Deliver presentation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Follow up</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section11-1524839912456534">
<title>Business Plan Components (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list16-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Executive summary (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr3-1524839912456534">Texas Department of Information Resources, 2011</xref>)
<list id="list17-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Issue</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Anticipated outcomes</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Recommendation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Justification</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Assumptions</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Limitations</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Current situation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Proposal</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Financial proof</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Conclusion</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Supporting materials</p></list-item></list>
<sec id="section12-1524839912456534">
<title>Executive Summary (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list18-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Written last</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Similar to article abstract
<list id="list19-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Summarizes problem</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Entices reader to read full document</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Includes highlights from each component</p></list-item>
</list></p>
</list-item>
<list-item><p>Content: (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr3-1524839912456534">Texas Department of Information Resources, 2011</xref>)
<list id="list20-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Business issue recommended idea would solve</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Anticipated outcomes of implementing idea; aim, benefits</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Description of idea; how project addresses business issue; identify decision makers: stakeholders/customers</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Why idea should be implemented</p></list-item>
</list></p>
</list-item>
<list-item><p>Rationale for why selected over other options</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Summary of key quantitative/qualitative data</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Description of impact of <italic>not</italic> implementing proposed idea
<list id="list21-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Assumptions relevant to recommended idea</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Limiting factors/constraints related to idea</p></list-item>
</list></p>
</list-item>
</list>
</sec>
<sec id="section13-1524839912456534">
<title>Current Situation (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list22-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Describes current situation/“the pain” clearly: What’s the problem? Why a problem?</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Presents problem in terms important to audience: current costs/issues</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States why situation problematic for whole organization, not just you
<list id="list23-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Emphasize effects on achieving mission</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Emphasize impact of situation; clarify “the pain”</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Don’t assume decision maker has your/others’ perspective</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Includes future risks if situation remains unchanged</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Straightforward, not whiney or scary/threatening</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section14-1524839912456534">
<title>Proposal (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list24-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Grand plan: What is proposed</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>How plan solves problem/relieves “pain”</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>How much, if anything, it costs—cover all/hidden costs
<list id="list25-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Demonstrate you see big picture</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>How much new income generated, costs reduced/eliminated</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>When payoff comes</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Costs: When incurred</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Addresses strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, threats</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Anticipates/preempts objections</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Explains what happens if ideas/assumptions incorrect</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Demonstrates how idea helps achieve mission—makes clear connection</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section15-1524839912456534">
<title>Financial Proof (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list26-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Demonstrates return on investment (ROI)/cost avoidance (CA)</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Shows ROI/CA calculation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Includes source(s) of numbers
<list id="list27-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Historical data—literature</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Industry standards—association, government agency</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Is simple/clear
<list id="list28-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Use charts/graphs, not raw spreadsheet data</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Put details in supporting materials section</p></list-item></list></p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section16-1524839912456534">
<title>Conclusion (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list29-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Summarizes problem/solution</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Refers to earlier points</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States: Spending $_____ generates $_______ in cost savings/new revenue</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Reinforces urgency/importance</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>States you have answer</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Ends with call to action: Adopt this proposal</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section17-1524839912456534">
<title>Supporting Materials (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1524839912456534">Molisani &amp; Graham, 2008</xref>)</title>
<list id="list30-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Appendix</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>References, sources</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Raw data (if needed); more detailed financial information</p></list-item></list>
</sec></sec>
<sec id="section18-1524839912456534">
<title>Business Case Presentation (<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1524839912456534">Mykrantz, 2007</xref>)</title>
<sec id="section19-1524839912456534">
<title>Presentation</title>
<list id="list31-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Quick</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Easy to understand</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Drives to heart of issue</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Logical/compelling argument/presentation</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Solves an organizational problem</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Supports organizational value(s)</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Recommendation: one to two pages, few/concise slides</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
<sec id="section20-1524839912456534">
<title>Presenter</title>
<list id="list32-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Has high standards/hard on self</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Thinks strategically</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Understands decision maker’s mind-set</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Pretests presentation . . . ideally on true skeptic</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Dares to be accountable; committed to achieving specific goals</p></list-item></list>
</sec></sec>
<sec id="section21-1524839912456534">
<title>Conclusion</title>
<list id="list33-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Writing business case an important skill</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Expected by many decision makers</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Must:
<list id="list34-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Highlight company/organization assets/strengths/achievements</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Fact-filled</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Address decision makers’ concerns</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Must be:
<list id="list35-1524839912456534" list-type="bullet">
<list-item><p>Logical/compelling/irrefutable/hard to resist</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Timely</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Well-organized</p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Grammatically impeccable</p></list-item></list></p></list-item>
<list-item><p>Business cases get easier with practice</p></list-item></list>
</sec>
